Project 05: Communicate Data Findings¶

Metro Bike Share - An Analysis of shared bike trips around Los Angeles from 2016 to 2020¶

(Data Source: https://bikeshare.metro.net/about/data/)¶

  • Student: Thomas Kallnik
  • Date: April 8th, 2021

During the project I gathered, assessed, cleaned and explored the metro bike share data set. This slideshow will illustrate the findings I made in the data as part of the explanatory analysis.

In which areas of LA did the trips take place?¶

The blue border confines the area where trips in LA where recorded.

Red dots stand for the start of a bike trip, while yellow dots show trip ending locations. (Only a sample of 5000 trips is shown)

In [112]:
# import gmplot package
df_map = df[["start_lat", "start_lon", "end_lat", "end_lon", "velocity", "distance", "duration"]].sample(5000)

lat_lim = [df_map.start_lat.min(), df_map.start_lat.max(), df_map.start_lat.max(), df_map.start_lat.min(), df_map.start_lat.min()]
lon_lim = [df_map.start_lon.min(), df_map.start_lon.min(), df_map.start_lon.max(), df_map.start_lon.max(), df_map.start_lon.min()]

gmap = gmplot.GoogleMapPlotter(34.05,
                                -118.25, 10)

# Draw border with min/max coordinates
gmap.plot(lat_lim, lon_lim, 
           'cornflowerblue', edge_width = 2.5)

# scatterplot on google maps with starting locations
gmap.scatter(df_map.start_lat, df_map.start_lon,
                              color='red', size=100, marker=False)
gmap.scatter(df_map.end_lat, df_map.end_lon,
                              color='yellow', size=100, marker=False)
    
gmap.draw("map.html")

The majority of the trips took place in LA downtown, Santa Monica, Venice Beach, San Pedro, Universal Studios and Pasadena.

Here are some of the longer trip routes across LA:¶

The orange lines show the 1000 biggest distances of starting and ending locations.

3 interesting statistics about the total amount of trips:

  • Distance mean = 1.3 km, Duration mean = 17 min, Velocity mean = 7.3 km/h (if start and end were connected by a straight line)</font>
In [114]:
df_map = df[["start_lat", "start_lon", "end_lat", "end_lon", "velocity", "distance", "duration"]].loc[df.duration > df.duration.quantile(q=.95)]

lat_lim = [df_map.start_lat.min(), df_map.start_lat.max(), df_map.start_lat.max(), df_map.start_lat.min(), df_map.start_lat.min()]
lon_lim = [df_map.start_lon.min(), df_map.start_lon.min(), df_map.start_lon.max(), df_map.start_lon.max(), df_map.start_lon.min()]

gmap3 = gmplot.GoogleMapPlotter(34.05,
                                -118.25, 10)

# Draw border with min/max coordinates
gmap3.plot(lat_lim, lon_lim, 
           'cornflowerblue', edge_width = 2.5)

# draw random trip routes
for trip in random.sample(range(0, len(df_map)), 1000):
    latitude_list = [ df_map.iloc[trip].start_lat, df_map.iloc[trip].end_lat ]
    longitude_list = [ df_map.iloc[trip].start_lon, df_map.iloc[trip].end_lon ]
    gmap3.plot(latitude_list, longitude_list, 
           'orange', edge_width = 2.5, edge_style="-")
    gmap3.scatter(latitude_list, longitude_list,
                              color='black', size=100, marker=False)
    
gmap3.draw("map3.html")

IFrame(src="map3.html", width='100%', height='400')

Looks like some of the longest trips were even from the beach to Downtown or vice versa (~25km)!

Now let's look at the amount of trips per month and their duration means over time:¶

The gap in 2020 must have been caused by the "Stay-At-Home-Order" issued on March 19th in California: https://www.ajmc.com/view/a-timeline-of-covid19-developments-in-2020

In [115]:
df_month = df.groupby(pd.Grouper(key="start_time", freq='M'))["duration"].agg(["count", "mean"])
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,1)
df_month.plot(subplots=True, ax=axes)
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0)
axes[0].set_ylabel("trip count [-]"); axes[0].legend("")
axes[1].set_ylabel("trip duration mean [min]"); plt.xlabel(""); axes[1].legend("")
plt.suptitle("Monthly trip count and trip endurances over the years 2016-2020");

plt.text(x="2020-03", y=16, s="Covid-19");

Probably the Metro Bike Share company just started their business in LA from 2016-2017. 2018 and 2019 seem comparable even though mean trip duration decreased and in 2020 obviously the pandemic hit the company. At the end of 2020 the remaining trips were probably not short trips to work but rather touristic trips after a long lockdown.

Now let's look at the trip counts for each month of the year (2018 and 2019):¶

In [116]:
axes = df.set_index(df.start_time, inplace=False).loc["2018":"2019"].groupby(["month"]).agg(["mean", "count"])[[("duration","count"), ("duration","mean")]].plot.bar(subplots=True, legend=False, title=["", ""]);
plt.suptitle("Trip data for each month of the year:");
axes[1].set_xticklabels(["Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Okt", "Nov", "Dec"], rotation=45)
axes[0].set_ylabel("Trip count [-]")
axes[1].set_ylabel("Mean trip duration [min]");

As expected, especially in the warmer and months like july-october (also tourist period), there tend to be higher demands for bike sharing. On the other hand interestingly the mean trip duration in december and january are pretty high.

Same Diagram only referring to weekdays (on the x-axis):¶

In [117]:
axes = df.set_index(df.start_time, inplace=False).loc["2018":"2019"].groupby(["weekday"]).agg(["mean", "count"])[[("duration","count"), ("duration","mean")]].plot.bar(subplots=True, legend=False, title=["", ""]);
plt.suptitle("Trip data for each month of the year:");
axes[1].set_xticklabels(["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"], rotation=45)
axes[0].set_ylabel("Trip count [-]")
axes[1].set_ylabel("Mean trip duration [min]");

Whilst the trip duration is usually higher on the weekend, the total trip count per weekday surprisingly shows clearly more bike rent traffic on working days (especially tuesday and friday). I assume a lot of people use the bike on working days for their short way to the job to escape the car traffic jams.

Now let's check out the categorical features connected to duration:¶

In [118]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(16,12))
for i, cat in enumerate(["trip_route_category", "passholder_type", "bike_type"]):
    df.groupby(cat).duration.count().plot.bar(ax=axes[i,0], title=cat, ylabel="count [-]", xlabel="")
    df.groupby(cat).duration.mean().plot.bar(ax=axes[i,1], title=cat, ylabel="duration mean [min]", xlabel="")
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=.3, hspace=.5)
for ax in fig.axes:
    plt.sca(ax)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.suptitle("Data grouped by the categorical features (trip counts and mean duration)");

  • There are almost no Round Trips compared to One Way trips.
  • Most trips were initialized from somebody with a monthly pass.
  • Most trips where conducted by monthly or walk-up passholders, but people with one day passes spent the longest time per trip in the mean.
  • Most trips were spent with standard and secondly electric bikes, but smart bikes where used longer per trip (in the mean).

The same graphs for distance instead of duration almost look respectively the same with one exception:

  • Annual passholders seem to ride longer distances compared to flex and monthly passes even though they spend less time on the bike.
  • As conclusion the annual passholders must have higher speeds which the following graph illustrates.
    • Consider that the mean velocity is a fictitious feature calculated from the direct connection of start and end location and is hence biased by travel pauses as well as actual routes/directions.

The following plots will show dependencies between starting locations and trip velocities, passholder types and bike types.¶

In [134]:
from plotly.offline import download_plotlyjs, init_notebook_mode, plot, iplot
init_notebook_mode(connected=True)
df_3d = df.drop(df.loc[(df.duration<2) | (df.duration>60)].index).sample(frac=.01)

trace1 = go.Scatter3d(
    x=df_3d.start_lon, 
    y=df_3d.start_lat,
    z=df_3d.passholder_type,
    marker=dict(
        color=df_3d.duration,
        size=2,
        sizemode='diameter',
        showscale=True,
        colorbar=dict(title='Trip duration [min]'),
    ),
    mode='markers',
)

layout = go.Layout (
        scene = dict(
            xaxis = dict (title = "Start Latitude"),
            yaxis = dict (title = "Start Longitude"),
            zaxis = dict (title = "Passholder Type"),
        ),
        title = "4D Scatterplot"
    )

fig = go.Figure(data=[trace1], layout = layout)
iplot(fig)

The plot shows, that the longest trips in terms of time appear to happen mostly around Downtown or Santa Monica from Walk-Up or One Day Passholders. There are no trips from Annual Passholders recorded in Pasadena nore from Flex Passholders at the Oceanside.

The speeds are well distributed even though the highest ones seem to be located in Downtown and Santa Monica. Smart Bikes can almost only be found at the Coast or near Universal Studios and all trips started in Pasadena have no recorded bike_category.
